description: From Middle English untime, untyme, ontyme, from Old English untīma (“an unseasonable time”), from Proto-Germanic *untīmô, equivalent to un- +‎ time. Cognate with Old Norse útími (dialectal Norwegian otime).

entries.meaning: (obsolete, often used in plural) A wrong time; an unsuitable or improper time.

verbs.description: untime (third-person singular simple present untimes, present participle untiming, simple past and past participle untimed)

entries.meaning: To cause to be done at the wrong time.

description: From Middle English untime, from Old English untīme.

adjectives.description: untime (comparative more untime, superlative most untime)
